From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-27
Subject: [OOSI1] Dockerfile: SHA-256 verification for git-delta .deb
         and fzf tarball

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside
the container, so an agent running inside cannot edit Dockerfile
directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any environment with
write access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

This patch is independent of the other 2026-04-27 patches and can be
applied in any order relative to them.

What this fixes (review item OOSI1, backlog id 7d3a91ef)
========================================================
Two GitHub-release fetches are unverified:

  Dockerfile:39 — git-delta_${VER}_${ARCH}.deb piped to `dpkg -i`
                  (which runs maintainer scripts as root during install)
  Dockerfile:55 — fzf-${VER}-${ARCH}.tar.gz piped to `tar -xz`
                  into /usr/local/bin (binary runs every Ctrl-T/Ctrl-R)

Both are pinned by version ARG but not by content hash. A compromise
of the upstream GitHub release lands attacker-controlled native code
with elevated trust at next image rebuild — the .deb postinst is
particularly broad. Distinct mitigation pattern from the curl-bash
sites tracked in backlog `1807f5f4` (those are the moving-target
installer scripts at lines 94/108/117).

Fix: download to /tmp first, verify SHA-256 against a hash literal
kept alongside the version ARG (one ARG per architecture since the
binaries differ), then dpkg/untar. When Renovate bumps the version,
the corresponding SHA-256 ARGs must be bumped too — the build fails
at sha256sum -c otherwise, which is the intended behavior for an
unverified version.

The patch ships PLACEHOLDER values for all four hashes
(GIT_DELTA_SHA256_AMD64, GIT_DELTA_SHA256_ARM64, FZF_SHA256_AMD64,
FZF_SHA256_ARM64). The maintainer must regenerate the real hashes
before applying — the per-version inline command is documented in
each ARG block. Do NOT commit the placeholder values; the build will
fail on first run, which is the intended behavior when the hash is
uncertain.

Sibling pattern to the existing
`R5-R6-devcontainer-supply-chain-and-caps.patch` (which uses the same
PLACEHOLDER pattern for zsh-in-docker.sh).

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  1. Compute the four hashes (commands documented in each ARG block).
     E.g. for git-delta v0.18.2:

       for ARCH in amd64 arm64; do
         curl -fsSL "https://github.com/dandavison/delta/releases/download/0.18.2/git-delta_0.18.2_${ARCH}.deb" | sha256sum
       done

  2. Edit this patch, replacing the four PLACEHOLDER strings with
     the computed hashes.

  3. cd <smudge repo root>
     git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-dockerfile-checksums.patch
     git add .devcontainer/Dockerfile
     git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): verify git-delta and fzf SHA-256 (OOSI1)"

  4. Remove backlog entry `7d3a91ef` from
     `paad/code-reviews/backlog.md`.

Then push.

---
--- a/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
+++ b/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
@@ -34,9 +34,31 @@
 
 # Install git-delta
 # renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=dandavison/delta
+#
+# OOSI1 (review 2026-04-27): the .deb is fetched from GitHub releases
+# and `dpkg -i` runs maintainer scripts as root during install — a
+# compromise of the upstream release lands attacker-controlled native
+# code with elevated trust. Verify a SHA-256 against a hash literal
+# kept in lockstep with the version `ARG`. When Renovate bumps
+# GIT_DELTA_VERSION, the matching SHA-256 ARGs must be bumped too —
+# the build fails at sha256sum -c otherwise, which is the intended
+# behavior for an unverified version.
+#
+# To regenerate hashes for a new version (run from any machine):
+#   for ARCH in amd64 arm64; do
+#     curl -fsSL "https://github.com/dandavison/delta/releases/download/<NEW>/git-delta_<NEW>_${ARCH}.deb" | sha256sum
+#   done
 ARG GIT_DELTA_VERSION=0.18.2
+ARG GIT_DELTA_SHA256_AMD64=PLACEHOLDER_REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH_AMD64
+ARG GIT_DELTA_SHA256_ARM64=PLACEHOLDER_REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH_ARM64
 RUN ARCH=$(dpkg --print-architecture) && \
+  case "${ARCH}" in \
+    amd64) EXPECTED_SHA="${GIT_DELTA_SHA256_AMD64}" ;; \
+    arm64) EXPECTED_SHA="${GIT_DELTA_SHA256_ARM64}" ;; \
+    *) echo "Unsupported architecture for git-delta: ${ARCH}" && exit 1 ;; \
+  esac && \
   curl -fsSL "https://github.com/dandavison/delta/releases/download/${GIT_DELTA_VERSION}/git-delta_${GIT_DELTA_VERSION}_${ARCH}.deb" -o /tmp/git-delta.deb && \
+  echo "${EXPECTED_SHA}  /tmp/git-delta.deb" | sha256sum -c - && \
   dpkg -i /tmp/git-delta.deb && \
   rm /tmp/git-delta.deb
 
@@ -45,14 +67,34 @@
 
 # Install fzf from GitHub releases (newer than apt, includes built-in shell integration)
 # renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=junegunn/fzf
+#
+# OOSI1 (review 2026-04-27): the binary lands in /usr/local/bin and
+# runs every Ctrl-T/Ctrl-R from the shell. A compromise of the
+# upstream release lands attacker-controlled native code with broad
+# user-level trust. Verify a SHA-256 against a hash literal kept in
+# lockstep with the version `ARG`. When Renovate bumps FZF_VERSION,
+# the matching SHA-256 ARGs must be bumped too — the build fails at
+# sha256sum -c otherwise, which is the intended behavior for an
+# unverified version.
+#
+# To regenerate hashes for a new version (run from any machine):
+#   for ARCH in amd64 arm64; do
+#     case ${ARCH} in amd64) FZF_ARCH=linux_amd64 ;; arm64) FZF_ARCH=linux_arm64 ;; esac
+#     curl -fsSL "https://github.com/junegunn/fzf/releases/download/v<NEW>/fzf-<NEW>-${FZF_ARCH}.tar.gz" | sha256sum
+#   done
 ARG FZF_VERSION=0.70.0
+ARG FZF_SHA256_AMD64=PLACEHOLDER_REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH_AMD64
+ARG FZF_SHA256_ARM64=PLACEHOLDER_REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH_ARM64
 RUN ARCH=$(dpkg --print-architecture) && \
   case "${ARCH}" in \
-    amd64) FZF_ARCH="linux_amd64" ;; \
-    arm64) FZF_ARCH="linux_arm64" ;; \
+    amd64) FZF_ARCH="linux_amd64"; EXPECTED_SHA="${FZF_SHA256_AMD64}" ;; \
+    arm64) FZF_ARCH="linux_arm64"; EXPECTED_SHA="${FZF_SHA256_ARM64}" ;; \
     *) echo "Unsupported architecture: ${ARCH}" && exit 1 ;; \
   esac && \
-  curl -fsSL "https://github.com/junegunn/fzf/releases/download/v${FZF_VERSION}/fzf-${FZF_VERSION}-${FZF_ARCH}.tar.gz" | tar -xz -C /usr/local/bin
+  curl -fsSL "https://github.com/junegunn/fzf/releases/download/v${FZF_VERSION}/fzf-${FZF_VERSION}-${FZF_ARCH}.tar.gz" -o /tmp/fzf.tar.gz && \
+  echo "${EXPECTED_SHA}  /tmp/fzf.tar.gz" | sha256sum -c - && \
+  tar -xz -C /usr/local/bin -f /tmp/fzf.tar.gz && \
+  rm /tmp/fzf.tar.gz
 
 # Create directories and set ownership (combined for fewer layers)
 RUN mkdir -p /commandhistory /workspace /home/vscode/.claude /opt && \
